[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Troubleshooting Scala compatibility issues**\n\nI need to fix some issues without running tests just yet. I'm wondering if the Gradle Scala plugin Zinc requires a compiler bridge on scalaClasspath. The original setup had testImplementation for the compiler, but that caused runtime issues with version 2.13. Maybe I can force the resolution of scala-library while keeping the compiler dependency? It seems complicated since I'm trying to compile with Scala 2.13 but target 2.11 runtime, which could cause binary incompatibility. Converting tests to Java might help, but tests need to stay in Scala, sticking with coverage requirements.\n\n**Configuring Scala compiler and runtime**\n\nI can write Scala syntax and compile it with the Scala plugin, but I need to avoid conflicts with scala-library. I'm considering using Scala compiler 2.13 while running tests with 2.11, but I'm concerned about binary compatibility since a class compiled with 2.13 might reference specific APIs that aren't compatible with 2.11. Even if our test avoids certain Scala collection APIs, Scala class dependencies could still pose a problem. I need to make sure the Gradle setup includes the right compilers and the compiler bridge, as the error says it's missing.\n\n**Configuring scalaClasspath settings**\n\nI'm thinking that the default scalaClasspath might automatically include both scala-library and scala-compiler. If I set it manually, I need to include the compiler bridge as well. Maybe it's better not to set scalaClasspath at all. Instead, I could try setting dependency constraints to force testRuntimeClasspath to 2.11. But I wonder if this would affect the default scalaClasspath which likely relies on the general classpath. It's a bit tricky to balance all these configurations!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_02781978bc1d564e0169f8ccb8f5a081919416ce2f4fc539b6\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"